{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Vgy2rDoR9TjWnvoSvaE9iH","type":"tool_result","content":"<persisted-output>\nOutput too large (47.6KB). Full output saved to: /Users/riccardocaranfil/.claude/projects/-Users-riccardocaranfil-bitrefill-minipanel-blank-night-2/623ec6ea-9901-40cd-91c1-46508d69a4ea/tool-results/b13p6vxcq.txt\n\nPreview (first 2KB):\nriccardocaranfil 42293  12,0  1,6 515804464 268032 s055  S+    8:57PM   0:05.03 claude --dangerously-skip-permissions --model sonnet --max-budget-usd 10 --output-format stream-json --allowedTools Bash,Read,Write,Edit,MultiEdit,Glob,Grep,LS,WebFetch --add-dir /Users/riccardocaranfil/bitrefill/minipanel-blank-night-2 -p # MiniPanel — Technical Specification\\012\\012## 1. Overview\\012\\012MiniPanel is a self-hosted, single-command product analytics platform. It ingests events from external applications, resolves user identities, and lets analysts, growth managers, developers, and support leads explore and visualize behavioral data.\\012\\012**Guiding constraint:** runs entirely locally — no external services, no API keys, no auth.\\012\\012---\\012\\012## 2. Technology Stack\\012\\012| Layer | Choice | Rationale |\\012|---|---|---|\\012| Framework | Next.js 16 (App Router) | Already in repo; full-stack with API routes |\\012| Language | TypeScript | Already in repo |\\012| UI | MUI v9 + Tailwind CSS v4 | Already in repo |\\012| Database | ClickHouse via `clickhouse-client` (no Docker) | Columnar storage; sub-second aggregations on millions of events; ideal for analytics |\\012| ClickHouse client | `@clickhouse/client` | Official Node.js client |\\012| Charts | Recharts | Composable React charts; works well with MUI |\\012| Testing (unit) | Vitest | Already in repo |\\012| Testing (e2e) | Playwright | Already in repo |\\012| Linting | Biome | Already in repo |\\012\\012### Starting ClickHouse\\012\\012The `./clickhouse` binary must be downloaded once (see §10). Run `pnpm dev` — it starts both ClickHouse and Next.js together via `concurrently`. See §10 for details.\\012\\012---\\012\\012## 3. Architecture\\012\\012```\\012┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\\012│                     Browser (React)                      │\\012│  /          /explore  /trends  /funnels  /users  /test  │\\012└────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────┘\\012                         │ HTTP\n...\n</persisted-output>","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"623ec6ea-9901-40cd-91c1-46508d69a4ea","uuid":"41940039-35c9-48c3-8da2-52f27a592c9a","timestamp":"2026-04-15T18:59:59.433Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"riccardocaranfil 42293  12,0  1,6 515804464 268032 s055  S+    8:57PM   0:05.03 claude --dangerously-skip-permissions --model sonnet --max-budget-usd 10 --output-format stream-json --allowedTools Bash,Read,Write,Edit,MultiEdit,Glob,Grep,LS,WebFetch --add-dir /Users/riccardocaranfil/bitrefill/minipanel-blank-night-2 -p # MiniPanel — Technical Specification\\012\\012## 1. Overview\\012\\012MiniPanel is a self-hosted, single-command product analytics platform. It ingests events from external applications, resolves user identities, and lets analysts, growth managers, developers, and support leads explore and visualize behavioral data.\\012\\012**Guiding constraint:** runs entirely locally — no external services, no API keys, no auth.\\012\\012---\\012\\012## 2. Technology Stack\\012\\012| Layer | Choice | Rationale |\\012|---|---|---|\\012| Framework | Next.js 16 (App Router) | Already in repo; full-stack with API routes |\\012| Language | TypeScript | Already in repo |\\012| UI | MUI v9 + Tailwind CSS v4 | Already in repo |\\012| Database | ClickHouse via `clickhouse-client` (no Docker) | Columnar storage; sub-second aggregations on millions of events; ideal for analytics |\\012| ClickHouse client | `@clickhouse/client` | Official Node.js client |\\012| Charts | Recharts | Composable React charts; works well with MUI |\\012| Testing (unit) | Vitest | Already in repo |\\012| Testing (e2e) | Playwright | Already in repo |\\012| Linting | Biome | Already in repo |\\012\\012### Starting ClickHouse\\012\\012The `./clickhouse` binary must be downloaded once (see §10). Run `pnpm dev` — it starts both ClickHouse and Next.js together via `concurrently`. See §10 for details.\\012\\012---\\012\\012## 3. Architecture\\012\\012```\\012┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\\012│                     Browser (React)                      │\\012│  /          /explore  /trends  /funnels  /users  /test  │\\012└────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────┘\\012                         │ HTTP / SSE\\012┌────────────────────────▼────────────────────────────────┐\\012│              Next.js App Router (Node.js)                │\\012│   API Routes          Server Components       Streaming  │\\012│   /api/events         /api/trends             /api/live  │\\012│   /api/users          /api/funnels                       │\\012│   /api/seed           /api/schema                        │\\012└────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────┘\\012                         │ @clickhouse/client\\012┌────────────────────────▼────────────────────────────────┐\\012│                     ClickHouse                           │\\012│   events   identity_mappings   (identity_map_updated)   │\\012└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\\012```\\012\\012Identity resolution is the only stateful, write-side concern. Everything else is read-only aggregation.\\012\\012---\\012\\012## 4. Database Design\\012\\012### 4.1 `events` table\\012\\012Stores every raw event exactly as received. Never mutated after insert.\\012\\012```sql\\012CREATE TABLE events (\\012    event_id     UUID           DEFAULT generateUUIDv4(),\\012    event_name   LowCardinality(String),\\012    timestamp    DateTime64(3, 'UTC'),\\012    device_id    Nullable(String),\\012    user_id      Nullable(String),\\012    properties   String,        -- JSON blob\\012    ingested_at  DateTime64(3, 'UTC') DEFAULT now64()\\012)\\012ENGINE = MergeTree()\\012ORDER BY (timestamp, event_id)\\012PARTITION BY toYYYYMM(timestamp);\\012```\\012\\012**Notes:**\\012- `LowCardinality` on `event_name` compresses well and speeds up group-by queries.\\012- `properties` is stored as JSON string and parsed at query time using ClickHouse JSON functions (`JSONExtractString`, `JSONExtractFloat`, etc.).\\012- Partitioned by month to keep pruning fast across large date ranges.\\012\\012### 4.2 `identity_mappings` table\\012\\012Maintains the canonical device → user mapping. A device maps to at most one user.\\012\\012```sql\\012CREATE TABLE identity_mappings (\\012    device_id   String,\\012    user_id     String,\\012    created_at  DateTime64(3, 'UTC') DEFAULT now64()\\012)\\012ENGINE = ReplacingMergeTree(created_at)\\012ORDER BY (device_id);\\012```\\012\\012`ReplacingMergeTree` on `device_id` ensures a device can only map to one user (last write wins, deduplicated at merge time). Queries use `FINAL` to get the deduplicated view.\\012\\012### 4.3 Resolved identity — query-time join\\012\\012There is no materialized resolved-identity table. Resolved identity is computed at query time:\\012\\012```sql\\012-- Canonical resolved identity for any event\\012SELECT\\012    e.*,\\012    coalesce(e.user_id, m.user_id, e.device_id) AS resolved_id\\012FROM events e\\012LEFT JOIN (SELECT device_id, user_id FROM identity_mappings FINAL) m\\012    ON e.device_id = m.device_id\\012```\\012\\012This join is cheap in ClickHouse because `identity_mappings` is small and fits in memory. The dictionary optimization (see §4.4) can be applied if needed at scale.\\012\\012### 4.4 Optional: ClickHouse Dictionary (performance)\\012\\012If the identity_mappings table grows large, a `HASHED` dictionary can be defined over it and used in place of the LEFT JOIN:\\012\\012```sql\\012CREATE DICTIONARY identity_dict (\\012    device_id String,\\012    user_id   String DEFAULT ''\\012)\\012PRIMARY KEY device_id\\012SOURCE(CLICKHOUSE(TABLE identity_mappings))\\012LAYOUT(HASHED())\\012LIFETIME(60);\\012```\\012\\012This is an optimization, not a day-one requirement.\\012\\012### 4.5 Numeric property detection\\012\\012Numeric properties are detected at query time by attempting `JSONExtractFloat`. A `schema` API endpoint pre-scans a sample of recent events to return property names and inferred types, used to populate the UI dropdowns.\\012\\012---\\012\\012## 5. Identity Resolution Algorithm\\012\\012This is the most critical piece of correctness in the system (BR-101).\\012\\012### Write path (event ingestion)\\012\\012```\\012receive event {event_name, timestamp?, device_id?, user_id?, properties?}\\012\\0121. Validate: at least one of device_id or user_id must be present.\\0122. If timestamp is missing, set to now().\\0123. Insert raw event into `events` table.\\0124. If BOTH device_id AND user_id are present:\\012   a. Check identity_mappings FINAL for this device_id.\\012   b. If no mapping exists → INSERT (device_id, user_id).\\012   c. If mapping exists with same user_id → no-op (idempotent).\\012   d. If mapping exists with different user_id → reject with 409 Conflict.\\012      (A device cannot belong to two users.)\\012```\\012\\012### Read path (all queries)\\012\\012Every query that returns events or counts users joins `events` with `identity_mappings FINAL` and uses `coalesce(e.user_id, m.user_id, e.device_id)` as the canonical identity. This means:\\012\\012- An event sent with only `device_id` will be attributed to the mapped `user_id` once a mapping exists.\\012- Retroactivity is automatic — ClickHouse reads the current state of `identity_mappings` at query time.\\012\\012### Invariants\\012\\012- One device → at most one user. Enforced by `ReplacingMergeTree` + 409 on conflict.\\012- One user → many devices. Natural: multiple rows with different `device_id` pointing to the same `user_id`.\\012- Merge is retroactive. No backfill jobs needed.\\012\\012---\\012\\012## 6. API Routes\\012\\012All routes live under `src/app/api/`. All accept/return JSON unless noted.\\012\\012### 6.1 Event Ingestion\\012\\012**`POST /api/events`**\\012\\012Ingests a single event.\\012\\012Request body:\\012```json\\012{\\012  \"event_name\": \"Purchase Completed\",\\012  \"device_id\": \"device-abc\",\\012  \"user_id\": \"user@example.com\",\\012  \"timestamp\": \"2026-04-15T12:00:00.000Z\",\\012  \"properties\": {\\012    \"amount\": 49.99,\\012    \"currency\": \"USD\",\\012    \"plan\": \"pro\"\\012  }\\012}\\012```\\012\\012Rules:\\012- `event_name` required.\\012- At least one of `device_id` or `user_id` required.\\012- `timestamp` optional; defaults to server time.\\012- `properties` optional; any flat key-value object.\\012\\012Responses:\\012- `201 Created` — event stored.\\012- `400 Bad Request` — missing required fields. Body: `{ \"error\": \"...\" }`.\\012- `409 Conflict` — device already mapped to a different user.\\012\\012**`POST /api/events/batch`**\\012\\012Ingests an array of events. Same validation per event. Returns `{ ok: number, errors: Array<{index, error}> }`.\\012\\012### 6.2 Event Explorer\\012\\012**`GET /api/events/list`**\\012\\012Query params:\\012- `event_name` (optional) — filter by name\\012- `resolved_id` (optional) — filter by resolved identity\\012- `before` (optional) — ISO timestamp cursor for pagination\\012- `limit` (optional, default 50, max 200)\\012\\012Returns events in reverse chronological order, with `resolved_id` computed. Cursor-based pagination avoids offset slowness on large tables.\\012\\012Response:\\012```json\\012{\\012  \"events\": [...],\\012  \"next_cursor\": \"2026-04-14T11:59:59.000Z\"\\012}\\012```\\012\\012### 6.3 Schema / Autocomplete\\012\\012**`GET /api/schema`**\\012\\012Returns distinct event names and, per event, the detected property names with types.\\012\\012Response:\\012```json\\012{\\012  \"event_names\": [\"Page Viewed\", \"Purchase Completed\"],\\012  \"properties\": {\\012    \"Purchase Completed\": {\\012      \"amount\": \"numeric\",\\012      \"currency\": \"string\",\\012      \"plan\": \"string\"\\012    }\\012  }\\012}\\012```\\012\\012Computed by sampling the last 10,000 events. Cached in memory for 60 seconds.\\012\\012### 6.4 Trends\\012\\012**`GET /api/trends`**\\012\\012Query params:\\012- `event_name` (required)\\012- `measure` — `count` | `unique_users` | `sum:<property>` | `avg:<property>` | `min:<property>` | `max:<property>`\\012- `granularity` — `day` | `week`\\012- `start` — ISO date\\012- `end` — ISO date\\012- `breakdown` (optional) — property name to break down by\\012- `breakdown_limit` (optional, default 10) — top N values; rest grouped as \"Other\"\\012\\012Response:\\012```json\\012{\\012  \"series\": [\\012    {\\012      \"label\": \"US\",\\012      \"data\": [\\012        { \"date\": \"2026-04-01\", \"value\": 142 },\\012        ...\\012      ]\\012    }\\012  ]\\012}\\012```\\012\\012### 6.5 Funnels\\012\\012**`POST /api/funnels`**\\012\\012Body:\\012```json\\012{\\012  \"steps\": [\"Page Viewed\", \"Signup Completed\", \"Purchase Completed\"],\\012  \"start\": \"2026-03-15\",\\012  \"end\": \"2026-04-15\"\\012}\\012```\\012\\012Returns per-step counts and conversion rates. Uses resolved identities. Respects event timestamp ordering within the window.\\012\\012Response:\\012```json\\012{\\012  \"steps\": [\\012    { \"name\": \"Page Viewed\",       \"users\": 1000, \"conversion_from_prev\": null,  \"conversion_overall\": 1.0 },\\012    { \"name\": \"Signup Completed\",  \"users\": 320,  \"conversion_from_prev\": 0.32,  \"conversion_overall\": 0.32 },\\012    { \"name\": \"Purchase Completed\",\"users\": 88,   \"conversion_from_prev\": 0.275, \"conversion_overall\": 0.088 }\\012  ]\\012}\\012```\\012\\012Funnel SQL uses a window function approach: for each resolved user, find the earliest timestamp for each step in order within the date range.\\012\\012### 6.6 User Profiles\\012\\012**`GET /api/users`**\\012\\012Query params: `q` (search string), `limit`, `cursor`.\\012\\012**`GET /api/users/[id]`**\\012\\012Returns:\\012```json\\012{\\012  \"resolved_id\": \"user@example.com\",\\012  \"first_seen\": \"...\",\\012  \"last_seen\": \"...\",\\012  \"identity_cluster\": {\\012    \"user_ids\": [\"user@example.com\"],\\012    \"device_ids\": [\"device-abc\", \"device-xyz\"]\\012  },\\012  \"events\": [...]\\012}\\012```\\012\\012### 6.7 Seed Data\\012\\012**`POST /api/seed`**\\012\\012Clears existing data and populates ClickHouse with realistic sample data (BR-102). Idempotent. Should complete in < 30 seconds.\\012\\012Sample data spec:\\012- 6 event types: `Page Viewed`, `Button Clicked`, `Signup Completed`, `Purchase Completed`, `Subscription Renewed`, `Support Ticket Opened`\\012- 70 users (50 fully resolved, 10 multi-device, 10 anonymous-only)\\012- ~12,000 events over 30 days\\012- Non-uniform distribution: power-law on user activity; `Page Viewed` ~40% of events\\012- String properties: `page`, `button_name`, `plan`, `currency`, `source`\\012- Numeric properties: `amount` (0–500), `duration_seconds` (0–3600), `ticket_count`\\012\\012**`GET /api/seed/status`**\\012\\012Returns current event count and user count — useful for verifying seed completed.\\012\\012### 6.8 Live Event Feed (SSE)\\012\\012**`GET /api/live`**\\012\\012Server-Sent Events stream. Polls ClickHouse every 1 second for events with `ingested_at > last_seen` and pushes them to the client. Used by the Testing page.\\012\\012Response is a stream of `text/event-stream` messages:\\012```\\012data: {\"event_id\":\"...\",\"event_name\":\"Page Viewed\",\"resolved_id\":\"device-abc\",\"timestamp\":\"...\",\"properties\":{...}}\\012\\012data: {\"event_id\":\"...\",\"event_name\":\"Purchase Completed\",\"resolved_id\":\"user@x.com\",\"timestamp\":\"...\",\"properties\":{...}}\\012```\\012\\012---\\012\\012## 7. Frontend Pages\\012\\012All pages are React Server Components (RSC) where possible, falling back to Client Components only for interactive elements. Navigation via MUI sidebar.\\012\\012### 7.1 Navigation Shell (`/`)\\012\\012Persistent left sidebar with links:\\012- Explore\\012- Trends\\012- Funnels\\012- Users\\012- **Test** (for developers)\\012- **Generate** (bulk event generation)\\012\\012Dashboard home (`/`) shows headline metrics: total events, total users, most common event in the last 7 days.\\012\\012### 7.2 Event Explorer (`/explore`)\\012\\012- Table of events, newest first\\012- Columns: Timestamp, Event Name, Resolved Identity, Properties (collapsed JSON chip, expandable)\\012- Filter bar: event name dropdown (populated from `/api/schema`)\\012- Virtual scroll / infinite scroll using cursor pagination\\012- Clicking a resolved identity navigates to `/users/[id]`\\012\\012### 7.3 Trends / Insights (`/trends`)\\012\\012Controls panel:\\012- Event name selector (autocomplete from schema)\\012- Measure selector: Count / Unique Users / Sum of / Avg of / Min of / Max of [property]\\012  - Property dropdown appears only for aggregation measures; restricted to numeric properties\\012- Granularity toggle: Day / Week\\012- Date range: preset chips (Last 7d, Last 30d, Last 90d) + custom date picker\\012- Breakdown selector (optional): property dropdown + limit\\012\\012Chart panel:\\012- Recharts `LineChart` by default\\012- Chart type switcher (BR-301): Line / Bar / Area / Table\\012- Sensible defaults: Line for time series; when only one date bucket, auto-switch to Bar\\012\\012### 7.4 Funnels (`/funnels`)\\012\\012- Step builder: ordered list of event name selectors (2–5 steps, add/remove buttons)\\012- Date range selector (same presets as Trends)\\012- Result: horizontal funnel bar chart showing user count per step, with conversion % annotations\\012- Drop-off percentage highlighted in red between steps\\012\\012### 7.5 User Profiles (`/users`)\\012\\012- Search input → calls `/api/users?q=...`\\012- Results list → click opens `/users/[id]`\\012- Profile page shows:\\012  - Identity cluster (user IDs + device IDs as chips)\\012  - First seen / Last seen\\012  - Event timeline: reverse chronological, same format as Explorer\\012\\012### 7.6 Testing Page (`/test`)\\012\\012Purpose: lets developers verify event ingestion and identity resolution without writing curl commands (BR-200, BR-101 verification).\\012\\012#### Layout\\012\\012Two-panel layout:\\012- **Left panel — Event Sender**: controls to fire events\\012- **Right panel — Live Feed**: real-time stream of incoming events\\012\\012### 7.7 Bulk Generator Page (`/generate`)\\012\\012Purpose: lets developers and analysts populate ClickHouse with large volumes of synthetic events to stress-test queries, verify chart performance, and simulate realistic scale — up to 1,000,000 events.\\012\\012#### Layout\\012\\012Single-page form with a progress panel that appears once generation starts.\\012\\012#### Configuration Form\\012\\012| Field | Type | Default | Notes |\\012|---|---|---|---|\\012| Total events | Number input | 10,000 | Min 1, max 1,000,000 |\\012| Number of users | Number input | 100 | Synthetic user pool size |\\012| Date range | Date range picker | Last 30 days | Events distributed across this window |\\012| Event mix | Checkboxes + weight sliders | Preset mix | Select which event types to include and their relative frequency |\\012| Identity resolution | Toggle | On | When on, a configurable % of users start anonymous and later identify |\\012| Anonymous ratio | Slider (0–100%) | 30% | % of users who have an anonymous phase |\\012| Numeric property variance | Slider | Medium | Controls spread of `amount`, `duration_seconds`, etc. |\\012\\012**Preset templates** (one-click populate the form):\\012- \"Realistic (10k events, 30 days)\" — mirrors seed data shape\\012- \"High volume (100k events, 90 days)\"\\012- \"Stress test (1M events, 365 days)\"\\012\\012#### Generation Strategy\\012\\012Generating 1M events synchronously in a single request would time out. The generation runs as a **streaming job** on the server:\\012\\0121. Client posts config to `POST /api/generate/start` → receives a `job_id`.\\0122. Client subscribes to `GET /api/generate/[job_id]/status` (SSE) to receive progress.\\0123. Server inserts events in batches of **10,000 rows** using ClickHouse's native protocol bulk insert (`INSERT INTO events FORMAT JSONEachRow`). ClickHouse can sustain ~100k–500k rows/sec on local hardware.\\0124. Identity mappings are inserted in a separate batch after event insertion.\\0125. Job completes when all batches are done. Total time for 1M events: typically 5–15 seconds on modern hardware.\\012\\012#### Progress Panel (shown during/after generation)\\012\\012- Progress bar: \"X / 1,000,000 events inserted (Y%)\"\\012- Estimated time remaining (derived from current throughput)\\012- Throughput meter: \"~142,000 events/sec\"\\012- Status: Queued / Running / Complete / Failed\\012- On complete: links to `/explore` and `/trends` to immediately explore generated data\\012- Cancel button: sends `POST /api/generate/[job_id]/cancel` — stops after the current batch\\012\\012#### API Routes for Bulk Generation\\012\\012**`POST /api/generate/start`**\\012\\012Body: generation config (see form fields above). Returns `{ job_id: string }`.\\012\\012**`GET /api/generate/[job_id]/status`** (SSE)\\012\\012Streams progress events:\\012```\\012data: {\"status\":\"running\",\"inserted\":50000,\"total\":1000000,\"throughput\":125000,\"eta_seconds\":7}\\012data: {\"status\":\"running\",\"inserted\":150000,\"total\":1000000,\"throughput\":148000,\"eta_seconds\":6}\\012data: {\"status\":\"complete\",\"inserted\":1000000,\"total\":1000000,\"elapsed_ms\":8200}\\012```\\012\\012**`POST /api/generate/[job_id]/cancel`**\\012\\012Sets a cancellation flag checked between batches. Returns `{ cancelled: true }`.\\012\\012**`GET /api/generate/jobs`**\\012\\012Lists recent generation jobs with status and row counts. Useful to see if a previous run is still in progress.\\012\\012#### Implementation Notes\\012\\012- Generation runs in a Node.js `async` loop (no worker threads needed; ClickHouse inserts are async I/O).\\012- Job state is stored in an in-memory `Map<job_id, JobState>` (sufficient for single-machine use; no Redis needed).\\012- Each batch generates random events using a seeded pseudo-random number generator (`mulberry32`) so distributions are reproducible given the same seed.\\012- The generator reuses the same identity resolution logic as the seed script (`src/lib/identity.ts`), ensuring correctness.\\012\\012#### Left Panel — Event Sender\\012\\012**Quick-fire buttons** (pre-configured payloads, one click to send):\\012\\012| Button | Event Name | Payload |\\012|---|---|---|\\012| Anonymous Page View | `Page Viewed` | random device_id, `{ page: \"/home\" }` |\\012| Button Click | `Button Clicked` | same device_id as last anonymous, `{ button_name: \"Get Started\" }` |\\012| Identify User | _(identity link)_ | same device_id + `user_id: \"test@example.com\"` |\\012| Purchase | `Purchase Completed` | `user_id: \"test@example.com\"`, `{ amount: 49.99, currency: \"USD\" }` |\\012| Signup | `Signup Completed` | new random device_id, new random user_id |\\012| Custom Event | _(form)_ | manual fields |\\012\\012**Custom Event Form** (collapsible):\\012- `event_name` text input\\012- `device_id` text input (optional)\\012- `user_id` text input (optional)\\012- `timestamp` datetime input (optional)\\012- `properties` JSON textarea with syntax highlighting (CodeMirror or simple `<textarea>`)\\012- Submit button\\012\\012After each send, show inline success/error toast under the button.\\012\\012**Seed Data button**: calls `POST /api/seed` with a loading indicator. Shows event count after completion.\\012\\012#### Right Panel — Live Feed\\012\\012- Connects to `GET /api/live` (SSE)\\012- Displays newest events at top (prepend, not append)\\012- Each event card shows:\\012  - Timestamp (relative: \"2s ago\")\\012  - Event name (colored chip by event type)\\012  - Resolved identity (device or user)\\012  - Properties (compact JSON)\\012- Max 200 events shown; older ones are discarded\\012- Connection status indicator: green dot \"Live\" / red dot \"Disconnected\"\\012- Clear button\\012- Pause/Resume toggle (pauses rendering, buffers in background)\\012\\012---\\012\\012## 8. Component Structure\\012\\012```\\012src/\\012├── app/\\012│   ├── layout.tsx              # MUI theme provider, sidebar shell\\012│   ├── page.tsx                # Dashboard home\\012│   ├── explore/\\012│   │   └── page.tsx\\012│   ├── trends/\\012│   │   └── page.tsx\\012│   ├── funnels/\\012│   │   └── page.tsx\\012│   ├── users/\\012│   │   ├── page.tsx            # Search\\012│   │   └── [id]/\\012│   │       └── page.tsx        # Profile\\012│   ├── test/\\012│   │   └── page.tsx            # Testing page\\012│   ├── generate/\\012│   │   └── page.tsx            # Bulk generator page\\012│   └── api/\\012│       ├── events/\\012│       │   ├── route.ts        # POST /api/events\\012│       │   ├── batch/route.ts\\012│       │   └── list/route.ts\\012│       ├── schema/route.ts\\012│       ├── trends/route.ts\\012│       ├── funnels/route.ts\\012│       ├── users/\\012│       │   ├── route.ts\\012│       │   └── [id]/route.ts\\012│       ├── seed/\\012│       │   ├── route.ts\\012│       │   └── status/route.ts\\012│       ├── live/route.ts       # SSE stream\\012│       └── generate/\\012│           ├── start/route.ts\\012│           ├── jobs/route.ts\\012│           └── [job_id]/\\012│               ├── status/route.ts   # SSE progress stream\\012│               └── cancel/route.ts\\012├── lib/\\012│   ├── clickhouse.ts           # ClickHouse client singleton\\012│   ├── identity.ts             # Identity resolution logic\\012│   ├── seed.ts                 # Sample data generation\\012│   └── schema-cache.ts         # In-memory schema cache\\012└── components/\\012    ├── Sidebar.tsx\\012    ├── EventTable.tsx\\012    ├── TrendChart.tsx\\012    ├── FunnelChart.tsx\\012    ├── UserTimeline.tsx\\012    ├── test/\\012    │   ├── QuickFireButtons.tsx\\012    │   ├── CustomEventForm.tsx\\012    │   └── LiveFeed.tsx\\012    ├── generate/\\012    │   ├── GeneratorForm.tsx\\012    │   ├── ProgressPanel.tsx\\012    │   └── JobList.tsx\\012    └── ui/\\012        ├── JsonChip.tsx\\012        └── IdentityChip.tsx\\012```\\012\\012---\\012\\012## 9. ClickHouse Client Setup\\012\\012`src/lib/clickhouse.ts` exports a singleton client:\\012\\012```typescript\\012import { createClient } from '@clickhouse/client';\\012\\012export const clickhouse = createClient({\\012  url: process.env.CLICKHOUSE_URL ?? 'http://localhost:8123',\\012  database: process.env.CLICKHOUSE_DB ?? 'minipanel',\\012  password: process.env.CLICKHOUSE_PASSWORD ?? 'password',\\012});\\012```\\012\\012Environment variables (`.env.local`, not committed):\\012```\\012CLICKHOUSE_URL=http://localhost:8123\\012CLICKHOUSE_DB=minipanel\\012CLICKHOUSE_PASSWORD=password\\012```\\012\\012A migration script (`scripts/migrate.ts`) runs on startup and is idempotent (`CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS`).\\012\\012---\\012\\012## 10. Local ClickHouse Setup\\012\\012No Docker required. Download the ClickHouse single binary into the project root once:\\012\\012```bash\\012curl https://clickhouse.com/ | sh\\012```\\012\\012This places `./clickhouse` (v26+) in the current directory. The binary is gitignored.\\012\\012### Running a local server\\012\\012```bash\\012./clickhouse server -- --path=.clickhouse\\012# HTTP:   localhost:8123\\012# Data:   .clickhouse/\\012```\\012\\012Stopping:\\012```bash\\012kill $(cat .clickhouse/status)\\012```\\012\\012The `.clickhouse/` directory is already in the repo with its own `.gitignore` that ignores all generated data.\\012\\012### Integrated dev script\\012\\012`package.json`:\\012```json\\012{\\012  \"scripts\": {\\012    \"dev\": \"concurrently -n CH,NEXT -c cyan,green \\\"./clickhouse server -- --path=.clickhouse\\\" \\\"next dev\\\"\"\\012  },\\012  \"devDependencies\": {\\012    \"concurrently\": \"^9.0.0\"\\012  }\\012}\\012```\\012\\012`concurrently` forwards Ctrl+C to both processes.\\012\\012### Running queries / debugging\\012\\012```bash\\012./clickhouse client --query \"SHOW DATABASES\"\\012./clickhouse client --query \"SELECT count() FROM minipanel.events\"\\012```\\012\\012### Database initialization\\012\\012A `scripts/migrate.ts` script (run via `tsx`) creates the database and tables:\\012\\012```bash\\012pnpm migrate   # \"tsx scripts/migrate.ts\"\\012```\\012\\012It shells out to `./clickhouse client --queries-file scripts/schema.sql`. The `predev` npm hook runs it automatically so first-time setup is still one command:\\012\\012```json\\012\"predev\": \"tsx scripts/migrate.ts\"\\012```\\012\\012`migrate.ts` uses `CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS` and `CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS` — fully idempotent.\\012\\012### Reset\\012\\012```bash\\012kill $(cat .clickhouse/status)\\012rm -rf .clickhouse/data/ .clickhouse/metadata/ .clickhouse/status\\012./clickhouse server -- --path=.clickhouse\\012pnpm migrate\\012```\\012\\012---\\012\\012## 11. Testing Strategy\\012\\012### Unit tests (Vitest)\\012\\012**`src/lib/identity.test.ts`** — verifies BR-101 (required by hard constraints):\\012\\0121. Anonymous event followed by identify event → all prior events attributed to user.\\0122. Two devices linked to same user → both device's events appear in user query.\\0123. Device mapped to two users → second mapping returns 409.\\0124. Identify event is idempotent (same device + same user sent twice → no error).\\012\\012These tests run against a real ClickHouse instance (test database `minipanel_test`), not mocks. The test suite creates and tears down the schema before/after each test file.\\012\\012### Integration tests (Playwright)\\012\\012**`playwright_tests/`** — end-to-end flows:\\012\\0121. `test-page.spec.ts`: fire a quick-fire event via Testing page, verify it appears in Live Feed within 3 seconds.\\0122. `explore.spec.ts`: seed data, open Explorer, filter by event name, verify results.\\0123. `trends.spec.ts`: seed data, open Trends, select event + measure, verify chart renders with data.\\0124. `funnels.spec.ts`: build a 3-step funnel, verify conversion rates are non-zero.\\0125. `identity.spec.ts`: simulate anonymous → identify flow via Testing page, look up user profile, verify merged timeline.\\012\\012### Manual verification scenarios\\012\\012Matching BR verification steps:\\012- **BR-101 Scenario 1**: Use Testing page → fire \"Anonymous Page View\" 4× → fire \"Identify User\" → open `/users/test@example.com` → verify 5 events.\\012- **BR-101 Scenario 2**: Use Custom Event Form to link two devices to same user → verify both sets of events in profile.\\012\\012---\\012\\012## 12. Feature → BR Mapping\\012\\012| Feature | BRs Covered |\\012|---|---|\\012| `POST /api/events` | BR-100 |\\012| Identity resolution logic | BR-101 |\\012| Seed data script | BR-102 |\\012| docker-compose + README | BR-103 |\\012| Event Explorer page | BR-200 |\\012| Trends page (count/unique) | BR-201 |\\012| Trends page (numeric aggregations) | BR-300 |\\012| Chart type switcher | BR-301 |\\012| Breakdown selector | BR-302 |\\012| Funnels page | BR-303 |\\012| User Profiles page | BR-304 |\\012| MUI theming, empty states, loading | BR-305 |\\012| Testing page + Live Feed | Developer UX (unlisted) |\\012| Bulk Generator page | Developer / load-testing UX (unlisted) |\\012\\012Nice-to-have (Tier 4) not in initial scope: BR-400 (saved analyses), BR-401 (autocomplete — partially covered by schema API), BR-402 (multi-event chart).\\012\\012---\\012\\012## 13. Open Questions / Decisions Deferred\\012\\0121. **SSE backpressure**: if events arrive faster than the client can consume them, should the server buffer or drop? Initial impl: drop (newest only).\\0122. **Funnel window**: should there be a per-user time window within which all steps must occur (e.g., steps must happen within 7 days of step 1)? Not in BRs; defer.\\0123. **ClickHouse auth**: password is `password`, set via `CLICKHOUSE_PASSWORD` env var (defaults to `\"password\"` in `clickhouse.ts`).\\0124. **JSON property depth*","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false,"persistedOutputPath":"/Users/riccardocaranfil/.claude/projects/-Users-riccardocaranfil-bitrefill-minipanel-blank-night-2/623ec6ea-9901-40cd-91c1-46508d69a4ea/tool-results/b13p6vxcq.txt","persistedOutputSize":48738}}
