{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016uwNF9LGoa61PMgupmGoDB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So in the default run:\n- Identity integration tests: 5 skipped\n- Users integration tests: 9 skipped\n- Total 14 skipped (these are both sets)\n- 10 failed (from other test files - migrate.integration.test.ts and clickhouse.integration.test.ts)\n\nSo the identity integration tests ARE being skipped in the normal run. But why? ClickHouse is running and `/ping` returns Ok.\n\nLet me look more carefully at the error for the identity file:\n```\nFAIL  src/lib/__tests__/identity.integration.test.ts > identity integration — real ClickHouse (minipanel_test)\n\n\n```\n\nThis shows the whole describe block fails, but all 5 tests inside it are skipped. So `describe.skipIf(...)` skips all the tests inside when `isClickHouseReachable()` returns false.\n\nBut `/ping` works! So why does `isClickHouseReachable()` return false? I think the issue is that the function uses a top-level await that runs before tests start, and there might be a timing problem where Vitest executes these module-level awaits before ClickHouse is fully ready to respond.\n\nLooking at the test setup, the client is created at module level with the URL and credentials, then `isClickHouseReachable()` is called immediately in the describe block. The function itself makes a fetch request to `/ping` with a 2-second timeout and returns false if anything goes wrong. So either the timeout is firing, or the response isn't ok for some reason.\n\n```\n\ntypescript\nFinishing the reachability check...\n```\n\nThe pattern I'm noticing is that when `CLICKHOUSE_PASSWORD` is explicitly set to empty string, the tests actually run and fail, but when it's using the default password, they skip entirely. This suggests the password environment variable might be affecting whether the connection check succeeds or fails.\n\nLet me reconsider the concurrent test e